		@H Historical Background @L
        Roman Hispania was a crucial province for the Republic and later the Empire. Many natural resources, agricultural land, and, crucially, gold mines would be found within it. @L@L
        Many legions would also be raised from the local populace, and it acted as an anchor in the west, securing the Roman territorial extent with a safe border that allowed for ample trade. @L@L
        Despite the Romanization efforts, some tribes would still retain their original culture, in stark contrast to Romanized Gauls who saw their culture merge with the Roman one. While there were some developments during the crises of the 3rd century regarding Gallo-Roman culture, it never returned to its pre-invasion nature. @L@L@L@L

